  }
}

\subtree{
  \title{Properties of coherent sheaves}
  \taxon{remark}

  \p{
    By definition, coherent sheaves are also of finite type, but since we are trying to build a hierarchy of finiteness conditions we should show that coherent sheaves are also of finite presentation.
    Then we will have that [coherent #{\implies} finite presentation #{\implies} finite type].
  }

  \subtree{
    \title{Coherence generalises finite presentation}
    \taxon{lemma}

    \p{
      Let #{(X,\OO_X)} be a ringed space, and #{\sh{F}} a sheaf of #{\OO_X}-modules.
      If #{\sh{F}} is coherent, then it is also of finite presentation.
    }

    \proof{
      \p{
        This is \stacks{01BW}.
        The idea of the (short) proof is to use that #{\sh{F}} is of finite type to build a surjection from a finite-rank free sheaf, and then the fact that the kernel of this surjection is also, by the definition of coherence, of finite type; this gives a finite presentation.
      }
    }
  }

  \subtree{
    \title{Finiteness conditions on subsheaves of coherent sheaves}
    \taxon{corollary}

    \p{
      Let #{(X,\OO_X)} be a ringed space, #{\sh{F}} a sheaf of #{\OO_X}-modules, and #{\sh{G}} a subsheaf of #{\sh{F}}.
      If #{\sh{F}} is coherent, then the following conditions are equivalent:

      \ol{
        \li{
          #{\sh{G}} is coherent;
        }
        \li{
          #{\sh{G}} is of finite presentation;
        }
        \li{
          #{\sh{G}} is of finite type.
        }
      }
    }

    \proof{
      \p{
        We know that, in general, coherence implies finite presentation implies finite type, so we know that [(1) #{\implies} (2) #{\implies} (3)] even without the hypothesis that #{\sh{F}} is coherent.
        But then, since #{\sh{F}} \em{is} coherent, [(3) #{\implies} (2)].
        Finally, we have a sort of domino effect: if #{\sh{H}} is a subsheaf of #{\sh{G}}, then it is also a subsheaf of #{\sh{F}}, and the property of being finite type is a property on a sheaf itself, not on its realisation as a subsheaf of a specific sheaf;
        in other words, any subsheaf #{\sh{H}} of #{\sh{G}} of finite type is also a subsheaf of #{\sh{F}} of finite type, and thus of finite presentation (since #{\sh{F}} is coherent);
        thus #{\sh{G}} is coherent, i.e. [(2) #{\implies} (1)].
      }
    }
  }

  \p{
    Now, at last, we get the full two-out-of-three property, and it is stronger than the partial results that we had for sheaves of finite presentation, in that we do not even need to assume that the sheaves are of finite type:

    \subtree{
      \taxon{lemma}

      \p{
        Let #{0\to\sh{H}\to\sh{G}\to\sh{F}\to0} be a short exact sequence of sheaves of #{\OO_X}-modules.
        If any two of #{\sh{H}}, #{\sh{G}}, and #{\sh{F}} are coherent, then so too is the third.
      }

      \proof{
        \p{
          This is part of \stacks{01BY}.
        }
      }
    }
  }

  \p{
    In fact, we have an even better result than mere two-out-of-three:

    \subtree{
      \title{Coherent sheaves form an abelian category}
      \taxon{lemma}

      \p{
        The category of coherent sheaves of #{\OO_X}-modules on a ringed space #{(X,\OO_X)} is an abelian category.
        Furthermore, its inclusion into the category of sheaves of #{\OO_X}-modules is an exact functor.
      }

      \proof{
        \p{
          This is the rest of \stacks{01BY}.
        }
      }
    }
  }

  \p{\todo{finally, the big property of coherence: (combining \stacks{01C0} with \stacks{01BP}) for coherent, SES on stalks implies SES on a neighbourhood}}
}

\subtree{
  \title{Coherence of the structure sheaf, and pullbacks and pushforwards}
  \taxon{remark}

  \p{
    Even though coherent sheaves give an abelian category when the other finiteness conditions did not, we have paid a price somewhere else: in general, it is \em{not} true that the pullback of a coherent sheaf is coherent.
    Even worse, there is \em{no reason} a priori for #{\OO_X} itself to be coherent, and so we cannot even ensure that (locally) free sheaves of finite rank are coherent — these \em{should} be a prototypical example of whatever sort of finiteness conditions we want, so the fact that the category of locally free sheaves is \em{not} necessarily a subcategory of the category of coherent sheaves is not a desirable outcome.
    But it turns out that the latter problem is somehow the only problem, in the sense of the following results:

    \subtree{
      \taxon{lemma}

      \p{
        Let #{(X,\OO_X)} be a ringed space, and #{\sh{F}} a sheaf of #{\OO_X}-modules.
        If #{\OO_X} is coherent, then #{\sh{F}} is coherent if and only if #{\sh{F}} is of finite presentation.
      }

      \proof{
        This is \stacks{01BZ}.
      }
    }

    \subtree{
      \taxon{corollary}

      \p{
        Let #{(X,\OO_X)} and #{(Y,\OO_Y)} be ringed spaces, and #{f\colon(X,\OO_X)\to(Y,\OO_Y)} a morphism.
        If #{\OO_X} is coherent, then the pullback functor #{f^*} that sends sheaves of #{\OO_Y}-modules to sheaves of #{\OO_X}-modules respects coherence: the pullback of any coherent sheaf is again coherent.
      }

      \proof{
        \p{
          Any coherent #{\OO_Y}-module is in particular of finite presentation, and pullback always preserves being of finite presentation;
          since #{\OO_X} is coherent, being of finite presentation implies coherence, and so the pullback is coherent.
        }
      }
    }
  }

  \p{
    The fact that #{\OO_X} itself can be non-coherent is "not surprising", since an arbitrary ringed space with no further hypotheses could conceivably have "too many functions".
    There are two particularly important results concerning ringed spaces whose structure sheaf is coherent: one in algebraic geometry, and one in holomorphic geometry; the latter is one of the fundamental results in complex geometry.

    \subtree{
      \title{Noetherian coherence}
      \taxon{theorem}

      \p{
        Let #{(X,\OO_X)} be a locally Noetherian scheme.
        Then #{\OO_X} is a coherent #{\OO_X}-module.
      }

      \proof{
        \p{
          This is \stacks{01XZ}.
        }
      }
    }

    \subtree{
      \title{Oka coherence}
      \taxon{theorem}

      \p{
        Let #{(X,\OO_X)} be a complex manifold.
        Then #{\OO_X} is a coherent #{\OO_X}-module.
      }

      \proof{
        \p{
          \todo{give a good reference}
        }
      }

      \subtree{
        \taxon{remark}

        \p{
          One reason that this result is so deep is that it is somehow stronger than the corresponding result in algebraic geometry, since #{\OO_X(X)} is not a Noetherian ring in general for complex manifolds (e.g. for #{X} a Stein manifold) and yet #{\OO_X} is still coherent.
        }
      }
    }
  }

  \p{
    Alongside Oka's coherence theorem, the other fundamental result for holomorphic geometry concerns pushforwards.
    Combining Oka's coherence theorem (or by assuming a locally Noetherian hypothesis, in the algebraic case) with \todo{the lemma about #{\OO_X} coherent implies pullback preserves coherence}, we obtain \em{functoriality of coherent sheaves for complex manifolds}, in that
    ##{
      \begin{aligned}
        \Cat{RingSp}
        &\longrightarrow \Cat{Cat}
      \\(X,\OO_X)
        &\longmapsto \Cat{Coh}(X)
      \\{}[f\colon(X,\OO_X)\to(Y,\OO_Y)]
        &\longmapsto [f^*\colon\Cat{Coh}(Y)\to\Cat{Coh}(X)]
      \end{aligned}
    }
    defines a (pseudo-)functor from the category of ringed spaces to the category of (dg-)categories.
    More simply, for \em{any} morphism #{f\colon(X,\OO_X)\to(Y,\OO_Y)} we obtain a pullback functor #{f^*\colon\Cat{Coh}(Y)\to\Cat{Coh}(X)}.
    It is then natural to ask if a similar stories holds true for a pushforward functor.
  }

  \p{
    In general, for an arbitrary morphism #{f\colon(X,\OO_X)\to(Y,\OO_Y)}, it is not the case that the pushforward #{f_*\sh{F}} of a coherent sheaf #{\sh{F}} of #{\OO_X}-modules will again be coherent (as a sheaf of #{\OO_Y}-modules).
    However, this \em{is} true if we take #{f} to be \em{proper} (by a result of Grauert–Remmert \todo{cite GR84, Theorem 10.4.6} in the holomorphic case, and Grothendieck \todo{cite EGA III, 3.2.1} in the algebraic case).
    Here we state only the holomorphic version; the algebraic version is \stacks{02O3}.

